  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering penalties can include significant fines and prison sentences. Generally, the penalties depend on the specific circumstances of the offense, such as the amount of money involved and the nature of the criminal activity. Some key potential penalties include:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Fines up to $500,000 or double the value of the property involved\n- Prison sentences ranging from 10-20 years\n- Potential asset forfeiture\n\n2. Specific Sentencing Guidelines:\n- Penalties can increase based on underlying criminal activity\n- Consideration of amount of money laundered\n- Prior criminal history\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Civil penalties\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\nHowever, I want to be clear that I'm providing general information about potential legal penalties. For specific legal advice about a particular situation, I recommend consulting with a qualified attorney who can provide professional guidance.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any part of this overview of money laundering penalties?",
